run argues that these democratic forms have profoundly influenced modern experiences of democracy, in particular the idea of government not as domination but as service. Dalarun undertakes meticulous textual analysis and historical research into twelfth and thirteenth-century religious movements—from Fontevraud and the Paraclete of Abelard and Heloise through St. Dominic and St. Francis—that sought their superiors from among the less exalted members of their communities to chart how these experiments prefigured certain aspects of modern democracies, those allowing individuals to find their way forward as part of a collective. Wide ranging and deeply original,To Govern Is to Serve highlights the history of the reciprocal bonds of service and humility that underpin increasingly fragile democracies in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPolitical theologyxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aPower (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aPolitical Theory. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aFrancis and Clare of Assisi, power of weakness, Robert of Arbrissel, pastoral government, governing as service, alternate models of democratic governance, medieval government, history of democracy.1 aField, Sean L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaposchkin, M. Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLester, Anne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176787640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501767876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501767876/original  a978-3-11